# Worship Metrics — Marketing Website Scope

**Reposition the site from "Tech Manager, the AV operations tool" to "Worship Metrics, the operating system for your Sunday."**

This document is the scope for a major marketing site overhaul. The site's current positioning is built around Tech Manager as the hero product. Our product strategy has evolved — Tech Manager is now one feature among several, and the paid-tier story centers on the new Services feature (service planning + production execution + Central Control integration) which does not exist on the site yet.

This is not a polish pass. This is a repositioning. The information architecture, the hero, the pricing page, and the feature-page relationships all need to change. The visual system, the Knowledge Base infrastructure, the founder story, and the underlying tech stack can stay.

---

## 1. Strategic Context (so decisions make sense)

### 1.1 What the product actually is now

Worship Metrics is becoming the **operating system for church production**. It includes:

- **Services** — service planning + production cue sheet + volunteer assignment + run-of-show execution. NEW. Free for planning, paid for Central Control-powered automation.
- **Volunteers** — volunteer management: capabilities, training, availability, scheduling, communications. Foundation for Services.
- **Worship Clips** — sermon clipping, free tier runs locally via Whisper in the desktop app, paid tier adds cloud sync, auto-publishing, social formatting.
- **Tech Manager** — desktop app for AV monitoring, device discovery, system documentation, Luminos AI diagnostics. Still important. No longer the hero.
- **Attendance** — computer vision + manual counting, in-room + online unified.
- **Digital Signage** — 40+ templates, Brand Kit, TV link. Free tier stays strong.
- **Luminos AI** — diagnostics inside Tech Manager, eventually throughout the platform.
- **Hardware** — Hub ($499) and Tablet (from $349).
- **Central Control integration** (paid tier) — Services feature integrates with Sistine's Central Control show control engine. Rundowns, Flex Macros, WebPanel-driven volunteer execution, MCP-driven cue authoring. The headline paid-tier capability.

### 1.2 The monetization spine

**Free makes you organized. Paid makes Sunday run itself.**

- Free: service planning, volunteer management, clip generation (local), signage (1 screen), attendance, Tech Manager desktop app, Knowledge Base, community support.
- Paid tiers layer on: cloud-synced clips with auto-publishing, unlimited signage screens, real-time monitoring with SMS alerts, Central Control integration (the big one), multi-campus, white-label.

Every feature page must reflect this spine. What's free, what's paid, and why the paid layer is worth it.

### 1.3 The buyer and the user

- **Buyer**: church tech director, executive pastor, or church admin. They approve the subscription line item. They read pricing and ROI language. They want to see it's legitimate enterprise-grade software.
- **User**: Sunday morning volunteers, staff, pastors. They use the tools. They rarely read the marketing site.

The marketing site is primarily for buyers. Tone should be professional and confident, not hobbyist. "Geeks" vocabulary stays on the content brand (Signal and Sanctuary podcast), not on the product site.

### 1.4 Signal and Sanctuary integration

The podcast/content brand Signal and Sanctuary will live on the Worship Metrics channel — same domain, integrated into site navigation. It is the top-of-funnel content engine that drives audience into the product. Site must accommodate this without making the company feel like a podcast with a product attached.

