## 5. Copywriting Guidelines

### 5.1 Voice

- Confident, not cocky
- Practical, not pitchy
- Speaks to tech directors and pastors, not volunteers (volunteers don't read marketing sites)
- Uses specific language — "your 10:47 stream drop" is better than "stream issues"
- Avoids "AI" as a buzzword; use it when real, explain what it does
- Never uses "empower," "unleash," or "revolutionize"

### 5.2 Repeatable phrases to establish

- "The operating system for your Sunday"
- "Free makes you organized. Paid makes Sunday run itself."
- "Stop running Sunday on one person's expertise." (existing, keep)
- "Plan your Sunday. Run your Sunday. Know how your Sunday went."
- "Powered by Central Control" (for the paid-tier branding)

### 5.3 Visual language

- Screenshots should show real UI, not illustrated abstractions
- When showing paid features, subtle "Pro" or "Central Control" badges on relevant screenshots
- Free features should not be apologetic — they should feel like real software, because they are

